label chapter15:

    # [Scene: Storm-broken Lighthouse | Dusk]

    scene bg ch14_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, slow strings; a single piano note lingers like a held breath]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind keening around the rusted railing; a gull calls once and vanishes]
    "You stand with the Atlantic pressing on two sides—one side memory, the other a flat, bright bruise where the town used to breathe easily. The watch is heavier than it should be. Salt has eaten the"
    "leather; the crystal is a fogged pupil. You turn it over in your hand until the small stamp—your brother's initials—catches the light in a way that feels like accusation and benediction at the same time."
    "The lighthouse lamp coughs behind you, a weak, mechanical blink that does not feel like comfort. The scaffolding's metal tang smells of rain and old electricity. Your hair, the single teal streak whipping like a small"
    "question flag, catches the wind and pulls your thoughts in the same direction—toward every promise you once believed could be kept."
    "You don't let yourself wonder if 'kept' ever meant the same thing as 'saved.' You only count: houses raised, houses abandoned; seedlings planted, seedlings lost; dinners served, quieted. Counting is how you try to make sense of unbalanced ledgers that measure human need in sandbags and shorelines."
    "A figure approaches along the rocky path—Tomas, shoulders bowed but steady, his boots dragging salt and gravel. He moves like someone who learned to forgive weather but never to forget it."
    show tomas_bianchi at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_bianchi "You stand out here long enough, the wind starts to teach you how to listen to what it takes. It don't ask permission."
    show maya_inoue at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_inoue "I was rehearsing apologies, Tomas. The wind is a good audience."

    tomas_bianchi "Apologies are warm pockets. They don't stop a broken roof."

    maya_inoue "I know. I know that. But—' You close your fist around the watch until the metal bites. 'I thought anchoring the referendum would slow the hand that moves too fast. I thought—"

    tomas_bianchi "Thoughts don't hold roofs, Maya. You know that better than anyone."

    maya_inoue "Then what do we do with them—these thoughts—when the sea keeps making claims?"
    "Tomas is quiet. He runs a callused thumb over a frayed knot on his sleeve, the motion small and intimate against the vast, indifferent horizon."

    tomas_bianchi "We do the things we can. We don't let the list be all there is to living."
    "You want to argue—about leverage, about pushing harder, about whether there was a line you should have crossed with LuxCorp—but the word 'if' tastes like rust in your mouth. Instead you press the watch to your"
    "palm and feel the dull rhythm of your own pulse. It is uneven, scarred by nights spent replaying choices like exam questions you can't study your way out of."

    menu:
        "Clutch the watch and memorize the time":
            "You press the watch to your ear until it's only your pulse and the sea. The time freezes on your tongue like an omen."
        "Slip the watch back into your pocket and look at the shore":
            "You tuck the watch away. Looking outward, you let the town's edges define what you will answer to."

    menu:
        "Gather the loose seedlings and plant them where the roots still hold":
            "Your hands go into the cold water. For a heartbeat a runner returns: a tender tug, a hopeful tremor. For another, the tide takes what it will."
        "Stand back and map the erosion instead":
            "You take out your notebook and draw the new lines. The map is clinical. The map will not comfort anyone, but it will be useful."
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
